Non-fraudulent manuel repetition of another work of art. The contemporary notion of Authenticity has tended to obscure the fact that the exercise of copying has been a central feature of art practice since antiquity. Unlike the forger , the copyist produces a worh that, while taking another work as its point of departure, is not intended to deceive the spectator. The difference in intention distinguishes the copy from the forgery; the use of any other methodological or aesthetic criterion may risk confusing the two. Although engravings or photographs after another work of art are obviously copies in one sense, as reproductions they emply a mechanical process that seperates them from the manuel copies under discussion here
